[{"id":27549,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Asp-Glu-Lys pripeptide is :</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e9c31d10-0124-4e34-950f-3354b4bd82c8-image.png\" style=\"width: 435px; height: 111px;\" /></p><p>No. of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CO</mi></math>&nbsp;group&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27415,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A-II, B-I, C-III, D-IV","A-IV, B-III, C-II, D-I","A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II","A-I, B-III, C-II, D-IV"],"answer":2,"solution":"Vitamin $B_1$ is chemically known as Thiamine.<br><br>Vitamin $B_2$ is chemically known as Riboflavin.<br><br>Vitamin $B_6$ is chemically known as Pyridoxine.<br><br>Vitamin C is chemically known as Ascorbic acid.<br><br>Therefore, the correct matching is A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II.<br><br>Answer: A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27471,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["asparagine","histidine","arginine","lysine"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Asparagine have only one basic functional Group Structure of Asparagine:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aef0bc5e-9116-4f40-96ee-4fda14c748f2.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 149px;\" /></p><p>There are three amino acids that have basic side chains at neutral pH. These are arginine (Arg), lysine (Lys), and histidine (His). Their side chains contain nitrogen and resemble ammonia, which is a base. Their pKa&#39;s are high enough that they tend to bind protons, gaining a positive charge in the process.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27429,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["valine-glycine","alanine-glycine","valine-leucine","alanine-alanine"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9_5eyGpLye-unYvUMEeojr3xmxrBAXuKDc8_-6edlQc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/i5hzLw-ZZyi-Nwn9Ct4EbCfkI4dtjX8p043ZZz1tNTs.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27440,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["(A), (B) and (C) only","(B), (C) and (E) only","(C), (D) and (E) only","(B), (C) and (D) only"],"answer":1,"solution":"$(\\mathrm{A})$ Starch $\\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{H}^{+} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}}$ Glucose\n(B) Cane sugar $\\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{H}^{+} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}}$ glucose + fructose (Sucrose) $50 \\% \\quad 50 \\%$\n(C) Milk sugar $\\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{H}^{+} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}}$ glucose + galactose (Lactose)\n(D) Amylopectin $\\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{H}^{+} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}}$ Glucose\n(E) Amylose $\\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{H}^{+} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}}$ Glucose\nSo, correct options are B,C,and E only.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27616,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["D-ribose","D-glucose","L-glucose","D-fructose"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/XXh4-VxITYpKJ2bjUYcM5TKXG7uagxE7WMfVkxHpW_g.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":27424,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A and B Only","A, B and D Only","B and C Only","A, C and D Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"Statement A is correct: Enzymes lower the activation energy barrier for reactions, making enzyme-catalyzed hydrolysis of sucrose have lower activation energy than acid-catalyzed hydrolysis.<br><br>Statement B is correct: Denaturation disrupts hydrogen bonds and hydrophobic interactions maintaining secondary and tertiary structures, but the covalent peptide bonds forming the primary structure remain intact.<br><br>Statement C is incorrect: Nucleotides are joined by phosphodiester linkages between the 3' and 5' carbons of adjacent sugar molecules, not between C1 and C4. Glycosidic linkages connect the nitrogenous base to the C1 carbon of the sugar.<br><br>Statement D is incorrect: Quaternary structure describes the arrangement of multiple polypeptide subunits; tertiary structure represents the overall folding of a single polypeptide chain.<br><br>Therefore only A and B are correct","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27503,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>deoxyribose, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo></math>deoxyribose","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo></math>ribose, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math>deoxyribose","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>deoxyribose, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo></math>ribose","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>deoxyribose, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math>deoxyribose"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Deoxyribo nucleic acid or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DNA</mi></math> contains <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-deoxy-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-ribose sugar unit, whereas ribo nucleic acid or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RNA</mi></math> contains <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-ribose sugar unit.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/38f247e7-e476-4d85-bd03-b7b9b9a3f3bd-image.png\" style=\"width: 216px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> deoxyribose in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DNA</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b0bf1b26-1425-4253-954e-2f053e377aa6-image.png\" style=\"width: 167px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-ribose in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RNA</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27437,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["(A), (C) and (E) only","(A), (C) and (D) only","(C), (D) and (E) only","(B), (C) and (E) only"],"answer":1,"solution":"Valine, Lysine and Threonine are essential amino acids.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27555,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Gluconic acid can form cyclic (acetal/hemiacetal) structure","Gluconic acid is a dicarboxylic acid","Gluconic acid is a partial oxidation product of glucose","Gluconic acid is obtained by oxidation of glucose with <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Gluconic acid <img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/841c0857-d13b-49f7-919c-6d6e010e957e-image.png\" style=\"width: 384px; height: 99px;\" /> is obtained by partial oxidation of glucose by tollen&rsquo;s reagent or fehling solution or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>. Gluconic acid can not form hemiacetal or acetal.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27439,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["(A)-(IV), (B)-(II), (C)-(I), (D)-(III)","(A)-(I), (B)-(II), (C)-(III), (D)-(IV)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(II)","(A)-(II), (B)-(IV), (C)-(III), (D)-(I)"],"answer":2,"solution":"(A) Sucrose $\\rightarrow \\alpha_1-\\beta_2$ Glycosidic linkage\n(B) Maltose $\\rightarrow \\alpha$ 1-4 Glycosidic linkage\n(C) Lactose $\\rightarrow \\beta$ 1-4 Glycosidic linkage\n(D) Amylopectin $\\rightarrow \\alpha 1-4$ and $\\alpha 1-6$\n\nGlycosidic linkage\nA-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27525,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b3c022f7-d389-4e82-945a-f5224f5c6c1b-image.png\" style=\"width: 199px; height: 153px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6cff6b25-e7fe-4a53-ac95-307958e6a2ec-image.png\" style=\"width: 174px; height: 168px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f8f7cad5-c726-4f9a-aa89-2f919d3a60d1-image.png\" style=\"width: 135px; height: 182px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cb650ffd-dce6-4dc6-8768-aab6279db0ff-image.png\" style=\"width: 197px; height: 165px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The correct structure of cytosine</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f8f7cad5-c726-4f9a-aa89-2f919d3a60d1-image.png\" style=\"width: 135px; height: 182px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27418,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["3","8","6","4"],"answer":2,"solution":"For tripeptides with 3 different amino acids (ala, gly, val) where no amino acid is used more than once, each tripeptide must contain all three amino acids exactly once. The number of distinct tripeptides is the number of permutations of 3 amino acids = 3! = 6. These are: ala-gly-val, ala-val-gly, gly-ala-val, gly-val-ala, val-ala-gly, val-gly-ala.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27466,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>β</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>δ</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Proteins are natural polymers composed of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>-amino acids which are connected by peptide linkages.</p><p>The smallest unit to which the protein can be broken down is called amino acids. The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>-amino acids are the amino acids whose one carbon contains both the amino group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced></math> and the carboxyl group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>COOH</mi></mfenced></math>. This type of carbon is called <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>-carbon. Thus, the amino acid that contains an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>-carbon is called an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>-amino acid.</p><p>Proteins upon acidic hydrolysis produce <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>-amino acids.</p><p>Hence, the answer is option B.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27532,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Pyranose","Ketohexose","Aldohexose","Heptose"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Fructose is a ketohexose.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0921023e-71d0-406e-a9ea-6c6afc31c959-image.png\" style=\"width: 228px; height: 249px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27489,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Overall reaction of metabolism of glucose in the body:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Extra energy used to convert &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>)</mo></math> into <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo></math>, energy left</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1800</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>900</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kJ</mi></math><br />Moles of water vaporised from enthalpy of evaporation:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>900</mn><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>45</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>900</mn><mn>45</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mtext>&#160;mole&#160;</mtext></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>360</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27460,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo> </mo><mi>CATTAGCT</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>TACGAAGT</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>GTACTTAC</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ATGCGACT</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A DNA molecule consists of two long polynucleotide chains composed of four types of nucleotide subunits. Each of these chains is known as a DNA chain, or a DNA strand. Hydrogen bonds between the base portions of the nucleotides hold the two chains together.</p><p>Adenine base pairs with thymine with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> hydrogen bonds and cytosine base pairs with guanine with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> hydrogen bonds.</p><p>As we know that in DNA molecule , adenine (A) always pairs with thymine (T) and cytosine (C) always pairs with guanine (G).</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c5fefee2-de89-4b80-a9ac-f0e3a48e5efa.png\" style=\"width: 809px; height: 146px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27524,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Uracil","Guanine","Adenine","Cytosine"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given structure is Thymine and Thymine being paired with adenine","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27492,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>A tetrapeptide is a peptide, classified as an oligopeptide, since it only consists of four amino acids joined by peptide bonds.</p><p>A peptide bond, also referred to as an amide bond, is formed between the &alpha;-nitrogen atom of one amino acid and the carbonyl carbon of a second.</p><p>Example&nbsp;of tetrapeptide&nbsp;is:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Tuftsin</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced close=\"}\" open=\"{\"><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>threonyl</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>lysyl</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>prolyl</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>arginine</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo></math>is a peptide related primarily to the immune system function</p><p>As we can see in this example</p><p>No. of Amino Acids&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>No. of Peptide bonds&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p><p>Hence, (number of amino acids) - (number of peptide bonds) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27508,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true.","Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","Statement I is false but Statement II is true."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3dcb755f-7cad-4577-af9d-fa71b1e723b4-9708357.png\" style=\"width: 330px; height: 176px;\" /></p><p>Maltose is composed of two <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>-glucose units in which <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math> of one glucose is linked to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></math> of another glucose unit.</p><p>As&nbsp;there is a free aldehydic group on one of the components of the disaccharides,It is a reducing sugar.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27547,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fdc4275f-1fc0-43ab-8bd5-8b651673c1cd-image.png\" style=\"width: 199px; height: 101px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>Threonine have two chiral carbon atom.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27599,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/OvoFysS0N6yiQ0c1Ji6Rg1eWI2p623IUtdWuTH2NMUs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DtahGgibBuDmSk1VI1kZtntZrZGiEQRs0gZWaIGWbW4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/IjsRstc44u13Onod6XN14MrQc-89nFOOAprEsqU6gSA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/vuwJOSh7UWLA15lgQyUsuCek_Ezh7zKS7YodomkTRBM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"The correct structure of thymine is\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/exzLsmCt5tgU7dAhIbEde7fZ0EH06JvoETQ55gHv9Vc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27607,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["carbohydrates","polypeptides","urea","proteins"],"answer":0,"solution":"It is a test characteristic of amide linkage. Urea also has amide linkage like proteins.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":27563,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["It is also named as invert sugar.","It is a non-reducing sugar.","The glycosidic linkage is present Between <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math> of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math> -glucose and <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math> of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi></math> -fructose.","On hydrolysis, it produces glucose and fructose."],"answer":2,"solution":"Sucrose is a disaccharide which is formed due to glycosidic linkage between <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>1</mn></math> of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>-</mo></math> glucose and <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo></math> fructose.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a79d2ffc-bc9c-4233-951d-34f58045ef89-eec186f4-fb10-4d3d-9584-c718061138cf-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 191px;\" /><br />Sucrose also named as invert sugar, and it is a non-reducing sugar.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27458,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kHSkeMNp45xGqhfcwmvTJVb5zXvHRyaxMqv5oBD_vVQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/IaX1mQJMBzJ6ayoGvX_VX8rLqy-Bfmk1apECtIcjqGk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/K4udPZGMplnZ2Mfq642Q2T8zpuGoTjYsjN4dNKs5Dko.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tVW1C6Y0vmtv6cB2NzBGvnyilSYPpLrRnOEBzIbBIE4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Structure of L-Glucose is\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/u6OPzx7u71GeXozFsSpiUaGRlBjSxU4pOfuaXEYtrjA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27434,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/btnvCm5GxUQeIklQ4PyQG-0NMD3-4IW1A3V6Q9VgLuI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qxPaYfwWoyHmpTWHlApQccrcQb8zNgdWJSrp2-ZwVlY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rw8eOBtQL-M3QBMhMFdNkZOGatBk6ix8cl0WzAB-Ue8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/SdtDaSU8ohoVZCkUF8rnOTnLqc8PcXpAOwwXHw6iW1g.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xWG874ez557DURS5pJ_9ZyZ4r5HlaV8z0JvNDmdacAw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27581,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo></math>iodohexanal","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo></math>Hexane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Hexene","Hexanoic acid"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>HI</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>14</mn></msub></math><br /><br />Glucose on prolonged heating with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HI</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo></math>Hexane.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27474,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["(A)-III, B-IV, (C)-I, (D)-II","(A)-IV, B-III, (C)-I, (D)-II","(A)-III, B-I, (C)-IV, (D)-II","(A)-II, B-I, (C)-IV, (D)-III"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Amino acids are organic compounds that contain amine&nbsp; and carboxyl &nbsp;functional groups, as well as a side chain specific to each amino acid. There are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn></math> standard amino acids that are used to create proteins.</p><p>One letter codes of the given natural amino acids are<br />Natural amino acid&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; One Letter Code<br />(A) Glutamic acid&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(III) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></math><br />(B) Glutamine&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(I) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi></math><br />(C) Tyrosine&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;(IV) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math><br />(D) Tryptophan&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(II) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> Correct match is<br />(A)-III, B-I, (C)-IV, (D)-II</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27578,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hNaK5KBui2szxINUbrQjF_JEcZXBnpBBQgIm-2CTqd0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Jwt8POzw3PFXagdv6UxYk_0RCJN7b5jIIHY0Alg5Ymo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/86bU7f9D4BfGQeSTyMRUYmyxyuNQpVqB_nN8y2sbjgg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/H0sxjT1QW1K459CsNNkpm_RvsqAA7YVMMxDC34PUANU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":27592,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Vitamin K","Vitamin C","Vitamin D","Vitamin E"],"answer":1,"solution":"B complex vitamins and vitamin C are water-soluble vitamins that are not stored in the body and must be replaced each day.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27565,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["D-Glucose","D-Fructose","D-Galactose","D-Glucose and D-Fructose"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0daef036-cd04-4b85-a052-5c7da62538a0-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 328px;\" /></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Maltose is a disaccharide which contain D-glucose as a monosaccharide. Thus, Hydrolysis of maltose&nbsp;with <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math> gives D-&nbsp;glucose.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27413,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["A-II, B-I, C-IV, D-III","A-IV, B-III, C-II, D-I","A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II","A-II, B-IV, C-I, D-III"],"answer":0,"solution":"Arginine is an essential amino acid and its one-letter symbol is R. Thus, A matches with II.<br><br>Aspartic acid is a non-essential amino acid and its one-letter symbol is D. Thus, B matches with I.<br><br>Lysine is an essential amino acid and its one-letter symbol is K. Thus, C matches with IV.<br><br>Glutamic acid is a non-essential amino acid and its one-letter symbol is E. Thus, D matches with III.<br><br>The correct matching is A-II, B-I, C-IV, D-III.<br><br>Answer: A-II, B-I, C-IV, D-III","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27442,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["(A)-(IV), (B)-(III), (C)-(II), (D)-(I)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(II), (D)-(I)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(I), (D)-(II)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(II)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ISPGYMP0OL-LZHgUTBMXmd6Bhvn55PiEcoHbQV_15bI.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kU7Lu9Hck2cfM3HVlk0ML06N_4c2WvcQISJkHOwlNn8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27507,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>-bonding interaction","dipolar interaction","van der Waals forces","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></math>-stacking interaction"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The secondary structure of protein refers to the shape in which a long polypeptide chain can exist. They are found to exist in two different types of structures viz. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math>-helix and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi></math>-pleated sheet structure. These structures arise due to the regular folding of the backbone of the polypeptide&nbsp;chain due to hydrogen bonding between&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a1af6b5c-1a61-4333-9087-3b1bc83747c8-9709760.png\" style=\"width: 50px; height: 42px;\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>NH</mi><mo>-</mo></math>&nbsp;groups of the peptide bond.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math>-helix Is one of the most common ways in which a polypeptide chain forms all possible hydrogen bonds by twisting into a right handed screw (helix).</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27588,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Biomolecules","question":"","options":["Cysteine","Methionine","Cytosine","Cystine"],"answer":0,"solution":"Thiol group is <math> <mrow> <mtext>-SH</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br />(i) Cysteine&nbsp;&nbsp;​<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0690c67f-d397-4556-8c7a-418f40fda039-image.png\" style=\"width: 203px; height: 134px;\" /><br /><br />(ii) Methionine<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a753af88-251d-4511-a6b5-f1e3ff0e1e4b-image.png\" style=\"width: 256px; height: 130px;\" /><br /><br />(iii) Cytosine<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8f04b19-374d-4ecc-8f4f-d8e035a7517a-image.png\" style=\"width: 121px; height: 162px;\" /><br /><br />(iv) Cystine<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6c7f4085-08fe-4731-8128-36638e280321-image.png\" style=\"width: 324px; height: 128px;\" />&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null}]